--- title: Preview Guidelines --- # Preview Guidelines Lookbook previews are part of the design system. They should
model credible product screens, not a separate documentation aesthetic. ## Default Preview Feel - Use neutral product
surfaces. - Prefer borders and subtle background changes over shadows. - Keep spacing compact. - Use `rounded-md` or
`rounded-lg` for framed examples. - Use headings at product scale. - Show realistic clinical, lab, public-health, or
data-workflow content. ## Avoid By Default - `bg-gradient-*` for preview shells or feature blocks. - Decorative
`from-indigo-*`, `to-purple-*`, `violet-*`, or broad `purple-*`. - `shadow-lg` and `shadow-xl`. - `rounded-2xl` for
standard product panels. - Large marketing-style stats, hero layouts, or feature cards. - Decorative icons in headings
when the icon does not carry meaning. ## Use Status Colours For Meaning - Red: destructive or error. - Amber: warning or
caution. - Emerald/green: success or completion. - Blue/primary: accent, focus, main action, or informational role. Do
not use status-like colours only to make cards look varied. ## Preview Cleanup Priority 1. Replace broad gradient page
shells with neutral product backgrounds. 2. Replace raw `slate-*` preview styling with semantic roles or `neutral-*`. 3.
Remove decorative purple/indigo feature blocks unless they become meaningful status roles. 4. Reduce `rounded-xl` /
`rounded-2xl` to `rounded-md` / `rounded-lg` for standard examples. 5. Replace heavy shadows with borders and subtle
surface layering. 6. Make examples look like application workflows, not marketing documentation. ## Good Preview
Contexts - Sample inventory. - Lab records. - Review queues. - Filter panels. - Export flows. - Validation states. -
Keyboard-accessible dense tables. - Settings and permissions rows.
